items.title: Documentation missing for the 2.0.0 release.

labels.name: type: docs
labels.description: Improvement to the documentation for an API.

items.body: It's been a week since the 2.0.0 release, but the documentation still points to the [1.0.1 release as latest](https://googleapis.dev/python/container/latest/index.html#). This has caused a few issues with dependencies as certain functions seem to be deprecated in the 2.0.0, and calls being changed however missing documentation means there's no way to figure out the changes required.

items.title: cannot import name 'cygrpc' from 'grpc._cython' (/opt/python/grpc/_cython/__init__.py)

labels.name: api: container
labels.description: Issues related to the Kubernetes Engine API.

items.body:
I am trying to use the plugin `google-cloud-container` in AWS lambda, but I am having the following issue.
`cannot import name 'cygrpc' from 'grpc._cython' (/opt/python/grpc/_cython/__init__.py)`

I have tried installing the grpcio explicitly and with some versions but still having the same issue.

python version: 3.7
google-cloud-container version: 0.5.0

items.title: Python method for `gcloud container clusters get-credentials`

labels.name: api: container
labels.description: Issues related to the Kubernetes Engine API.

labels.name: type: question
labels.description: Request for information or clarification. Not an issue.

items.body:
I need a Python client library method equivalent to [`gcloud container clusters get-credentials`](https://cloud.google.com/sdk/gcloud/reference/container/clusters/get-credentials) so I can query for Kubernetes Job status from a Google Cloud Function in Python.

As far as I can tell, `get-credentials` makes a GET request for a cluster and then applies some magic to turn the response into a kubeconfig file. I think I can make the same GET request in Python with [this method](https://googleapis.dev/python/container/latest/gapic/v1/api.html#google.cloud.container_v1.ClusterManagerClient.get_cluster), but I don't see any way to turn the response into a kubeconfig file.

Please let me know if I've overlooked something in the Python client library.
